    <li class="comment odd alt depth-2" id="li-comment-1599014">

      <div class="grid group comment-wrap" id="comment-1599014">

        <div class="comment-avatar grid-1-5">
          <img src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAP///wAAACH5BAAAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw==" class="lazyload-gravatar" alt="User Avatar" data-src="https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/2c1a222a5b48d83a988fe206640bd4e6?s=160&amp;d=retro&amp;r=pg" width="50" height="50">
        </div>

        <div class="comment-body group grid-4-5">

          <div class="comment-author-wrap vcard">
            <div class="comment-author">Kazi</div> <div class="comment-time"><a href="https://css-tricks.com/snippets/css/a-guide-to-flexbox/#comment-1599014"><span class="screen-reader">Permalink to comment</span>#</a> <time datetime="2016-01-12T10:14:14+00:00">January 12, 2016</time></div>
            
          </div>
          
          <div class="comment-content">

            <p>@Josh McCullough its pretty simple to achieve that, 
better and easier then ever before. Just use the flex property and set 
it to 1, for e.g:</p>
<pre><code>.someClass {
   flex: 1;
   color: #ebebeb;
   padding: 2rem;
}
</code></pre>
<p>flex is a very powerful property and can be used in the shorthand of 
flex: 1 1 auto; (grow, shrink and basis) – using just flex: 1 tells it 
to take all the remaining space thus making the footer stick at the 
bottom. Look an eye out for grid to make a proper entry into the 
browsers and we would be having magic on our plates in terms of layouts.</p>
<p>See it live in action:<br>
<iframe id="cp_embed_WrOqma" src="layout-guide_files/WrOqma.html" scrolling="no" allowtransparency="true" class="cp_embed_iframe" style="width: 100%; overflow: hidden;" height="300" frameborder="0"></iframe></p>

            <div class="reply">
                          </div><!-- .reply -->

          </div>
        </div>
