  <ul class="children">

    <li class="comment even depth-2" id="li-comment-1581238">

      <div class="grid group comment-wrap" id="comment-1581238">

        <div class="comment-avatar grid-1-5">
          <img src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAP///wAAACH5BAAAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw==" class="lazyload-gravatar" alt="User Avatar" data-src="https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/b1aae07208e8c9d56480c82d2f6f1555?s=160&amp;d=retro&amp;r=pg" width="50" height="50">
        </div>

        <div class="comment-body group grid-4-5">

          <div class="comment-author-wrap vcard">
            <div class="comment-author">Jay</div> <div class="comment-time"><a href="https://css-tricks.com/snippets/css/a-guide-to-flexbox/#comment-1581238"><span class="screen-reader">Permalink to comment</span>#</a> <time datetime="2014-05-15T04:21:50+00:00">May 15, 2014</time></div>
            
          </div>
          
          <div class="comment-content">

            <p>Hi Stephen, I believe that justify-content isn’t to be 
used for this purpose. If you flow the elements by column (vertically), 
the justify-content: center will really display the elements in the 
center bit of the flex box vertically, i,e, some space at the top, then 
your elements, then some space at the bottom. What you wanted is for 
each element to center align horizontally, which you can probably 
achieve by using text-align property.</p>

            <div class="reply">
                          </div><!-- .reply -->

          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    
